ParaLine.String: Individual electoral registration in Great Britain
Individual registration
After section 10ZB of the Representation of the People Act 1983 insert
Registration of electors in Great Britain
A registration officer in Great Britain must enter a person (\xd2 P\xd3 ) in a
register maintained by the officer if
an application for registration is made by someone who appears
to the officer to be P,
any requirements imposed by or under this Act in relation to
the application are met, and
P appears to the officer to be entitled to be registered in the
register.
In determining an application under this section, the officer must
consider any objection made in accordance with the prescribed
requirements by another person whose name appears in the register.
Regulations may make provision about the procedure for determining
applications under this section.\xd3
Schedule
contains amendments about the alteration of registers and removal
from a register.
Registration officers in Great Britain must have regard to any guidance given
by the Minister about the determination of applications under section
10ZC of
the 1983 Act.
The guidance that may be given includes guidance about the process for
determining whether the conditions in subsection (1) of that section are met
and the relative weight to be given to different kinds of evidence.
Subsections (3) and (4) cease to have effect at the end of the period of 5 years
beginning with the day on which they come fully into force.
Applications for registration and verification of entitlement etc
Schedule 2 to the Representation of the People Act 1983 (provisions which may
be contained in regulations as to registration etc) is amended as follows.
In paragraph 1, after sub-paragraph (2) insert
Provision made under sub-paragraph (2) authorising or requiring a
registration officer in Great Britain to
require a person who has made an application under section
10ZC or 10ZD to provide evidence that he or she is the person
named in the application, or
require a person who has made an application under section
10ZC or 10ZD, or any person who has an entry in a register,
to provide evidence for the purpose of enabling the officer to
determine whether a person is entitled to be registered in a
register maintained by the officer,
must specify the kind of evidence that a person may be required to
provide (for examples, see paragraph 3ZA(5)).
Provision of the kind mentioned in sub-paragraph (2A) may
authorise or require the registration officer to require a person to
provide the evidence to a registration officer or to some other
prescribed person (or person of a prescribed description).\xd3
After paragraph 3 insert
Provision about applications under section 10ZC or 10ZD, including
in particular provision about
the form and contents of applications and of any declarations
to be made in connection with them;
the manner in which applications are to be made.
Provision made under sub-paragraph (1) may include provision
conferring functions on registration officers, or local or public
authorities, to enable applications to be made in a particular
manner;
conferring other functions on registration officers;
conferring functions on the Electoral Commission.
Provision requiring a person making an application under section
10ZC or 10ZD
to provide evidence that he or she is the person named in the
application;
to provide evidence of entitlement to be registered.
Provision made under sub-paragraph (3) must specify the kind of
evidence that a person is required to provide.
Examples of the evidence that may be specified include a person\xd5 s
date of birth or national insurance number.
Provision made under sub-paragraph (3) may require a person to
provide the evidence to a registration officer or to some other
prescribed person (or person of a prescribed description).\xd3
After paragraph 8A insert
Provision authorising or requiring a registration officer in
determining an application under section 10ZC or 10ZD, in
prescribed cases, to treat a prescribed person\xd5 s statement of a fact as
sufficient evidence of that fact.
In sub-paragraph (1) \xd2 prescribed\xd3 includes of a prescribed
description.\xd3
In section 201 of the Representation of the People Act 1983 (regulations), before
subsection (3) insert
Regulations made for the purposes only of omitting a particular kind of
evidence from the kinds of evidence that a person is or may be required
to provide by virtue of regulations under paragraph 1(2A) or 3ZA(3) of
Schedule 2 shall be subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of
either House of Parliament (and subsection (2) does not apply to
regulations made for those purposes only).\xd3
Schedule
to this Act contains amendments related to this section.
Proxies to be registered electors
In paragraph 6 of Schedule 4 to the Representation of the People Act 2000
(absent voting in Great Britain), for sub-paragraphs (3) and (4) substitute
A person is not capable of being appointed to vote, or voting, as proxy
at a parliamentary election unless the person is or will be registered in
a register of parliamentary electors in Great Britain or Northern
Ireland.
A person is not capable of being appointed to vote, or voting, as proxy
at a local government election unless the person is or will be registered
in a register of local government electors in Great Britain or Northern
Ireland.
A person is not capable of being appointed to vote, or voting, as proxy
at a parliamentary or local government election if the person is subject
to any legal incapacity (age apart) to vote at that election as an elector.\xd3
Annual canvass
After section 9C of the Representation of the People Act 1983 insert
Maintenance of registers: duty to conduct canvass in Great Britain
Each registration officer in Great Britain must conduct an annual
canvass in relation to the area for which the officer acts.
The purpose of the canvass is to ascertain
the names and addresses of persons who are entitled to be
registered in a register maintained by the officer but who are not
registered;
those persons who are registered in such a register but who are
not entitled to be registered.
The canvass is to be conducted in a manner to be set out in regulations.
The regulations may confer functions on the Electoral Commission (for
example, the Commission may be required to design a canvass form).
A registration officer may make house to house inquiries for the
purposes of the canvass, for example
to obtain information before sending out a canvass form,
to supplement information provided on a canvass form, or
to obtain information where no canvass form is returned.
Nothing in this section applies in relation to
the registration of persons in respect of residence in penal
institutions (within the meaning of section 3) or mental
hospitals (within the meaning of section 7) or other places at
which persons to whom section 7A applies may be detained,
the registration of persons in pursuance of declarations of local
connection, service declarations or overseas electors\xd5
declarations, or
the registration of persons with anonymous entries in the
register.\xd3
Invitations to register

Maintenance of registers: invitations to register in Great Britain
A registration officer in Great Britain must give a person an invitation
to apply for registration in a register maintained by the officer if
the officer is aware of the person\xd5 s name and address,
the person is not registered in the register, and
the officer has reason to believe that the person may be entitled
to be registered in the register.

subsection

Consulting Electoral Commission about proposals under section
If the Minister consults the Electoral Commission about a proposal to make an

The objective is to assist registration officers in Great Britain to ascertain

but who are entitled to be registered;
those persons who are registered in a register but who are not entitled

The Electoral Commission must give a copy of the report to the Minister by the

An order under section
may be made so as to have effect in relation to a

An order which, by virtue of subsection (1), is to have effect in relation to a
limited period is referred to in this section as a \xd2 pilot scheme\xd3 .
The Minister may make a pilot scheme applying in relation to an area only if
the registration officer for that area has
proposed the making of a pilot scheme in relation to that area, and

A pilot scheme may be replaced by a further pilot scheme.
If a pilot scheme is made, the Electoral Commission must

Financial provisions
There is to be paid out of money provided by Parliament
any expenditure incurred by a Minister of the Crown in consequence of
this Act, and
any increase attributable to this Act in the sums payable under any
other Act out of money so provided.

this Act in the sums payable under any other Act out of that Fund.
Meaning of \xd2 the Minister\xd3 etc
In this Act \xd2 the Minister\xd3 means the Lord President of the Council or the
Secretary of State.
In article 3(1) of the Lord President of the Council Order 2010 (S.I. 2010/1837)
(which makes certain functions of the Secretary of State exercisable
concurrently with the Lord President) a reference to an enactment that is
amended by this Act is to that enactment as amended.
Extent
An amendment or repeal made by this Act has the same extent as the
enactment (or part of an enactment) amended or repealed.
Commencement
Subject as follows, Parts 1 and 2 of this Act come into force on such day as the
Minister may by order made by statutory instrument appoint.
Paragraph 28 of Schedule
comes into force at the end of the period of 2
months beginning with the day on which this Act is passed.
This Part comes into force on the day on which this Act is passed.
An order under subsection (1) may appoint different days for different
purposes (including different days for different parts of the United Kingdom).
The Minister may by order made by statutory instrument make transitional,
transitory or saving provision in connection with the coming into force of any
provision of this Act.

ParaLine.String: Section
Register of electors: alterations and removal
After section 10ZC of the Representation of the People Act 1983 insert
Registration of electors in Great Britain: alterations
A registration officer in Great Britain must alter the name or address
in respect of which a person (\xd2 P\xd3 ) is registered in a register
maintained by the officer if
an application for alteration is made by someone who
appears to the officer to be P,
any requirements imposed by or under this Act in relation to
the application are met, and
P appears to the officer to be entitled to be registered in the
register in respect of the new name or the new address (as the
case may be).
In determining an application under this section, the officer must
consider any objection made in accordance with the prescribed
requirements by another person whose name appears in the register.
Regulations may make provision about the procedure for
determining applications under this section.
Removal of electors in Great Britain from register
Where a person is entered in a register in respect of an address in
Great Britain, the person is entitled to remain registered until the

ParaLine.String: Section
Civil penalty for failing to make application when required by registration
officer
In the Representation of the People Act 1983, before Schedule A1 insert
Section 9E
Civil penalties under section 9E
Introduction
This Schedule is about civil penalties under section 9E.
Amount
The amount of a civil penalty is to be specified in regulations.
Procedure
The procedure for imposing a civil penalty on a person is to be set
out in regulations.
The regulations must, in particular, require the registration officer
to give the person written notice specifying
the amount of the penalty,
the reasons for imposing it, and
the date by which and manner in which it is to be paid.
Regulations may specify steps that a registration officer must take
before imposing a civil penalty.
Reviews and appeals
Regulations may give a person on whom a civil penalty is
imposed
a right to request a review of the decision to impose the
penalty;
a right to appeal against the decision to the First-tier
Tribunal.
Regulations under this paragraph may, in particular
specify the grounds on which a person may request a
review or appeal;
specify the time within which a person must request a
review or appeal;
require a person to request a review before appealing;
make provision about the procedure for a review;
make further provision about reviews and appeals
(including provision as to the powers available on a review
or appeal).
Power to create exceptions
Regulations may specify circumstances in which
a civil penalty may not be imposed, or
a civil penalty may be cancelled.
Accounts and record keeping
Regulations may impose duties on registration officers about the
keeping of accounts and other records in connection with civil
penalties.
Interest and enforcement etc.
Regulations may
allow interest to be charged on a civil penalty that is paid
late;
allow an additional penalty to be imposed for late
payment.
In this Schedule \xd2 civil penalty\xd3 includes any interest or additional
penalty.
Regulations may make provision about the recovery of civil
penalties by registration officers.
A civil penalty received by a registration officer is to be paid into
the Consolidated Fund.
Power to make further provision
Regulations may make further provision about civil penalties.\xd3

Registration officers to invite applications in year of first new canvass from those with existing
registrations
A registration officer in Great Britain must, within a prescribed period, give
an invitation to make a new application for registration in a register
maintained by the officer to each person who
has an entry in the register but has not had his or her entitlement to
remain registered confirmed, and
has not made a new application for registration.
But the officer need not give an invitation at a time when the officer has
reason to believe, from records available to the officer, that the person is no
longer resident at the address to which the entry relates.
The period prescribed for the purposes of this paragraph must begin in the
year in which the first new canvass begins.
Powers to delay canvasses and timing of canvasses
The Minister may by order
postpone any canvass to be conducted under section
10(1) of the
Representation of the People Act 1983;
make provision about the period during which canvass forms to be
used for the purpose of such a canvass are to be given.
The Minister may by order postpone the first new canvass.
Any canvass forms to be used by a registration officer for the purpose of the
first new canvass must be given within the period prescribed for the
purposes of paragraph
The Minister may by order make provision about the period during which
any canvass forms to be used for the purpose of the second new canvass are
to be given.
A registration officer is not required, before the commencement date, to do
anything for the purpose of conducting any canvass under section 10(1) of
the Representation of the People Act 1983 by reference to residence on the 15
October after the commencement date.
An order under sub-paragraph (1) or (2) postponing a canvass must specify
the period during which it is to be conducted; and the period must not end
later than the 1
April after it begins.
An order under sub-paragraph (1) or (2) postponing a canvass does not
postpone or remove a duty to conduct any other canvass.
Canvass forms need not be supplied to addresses to which invitations supplied
At the first new canvass, a registration officer is not required to supply a
canvass form to an address if the officer thinks that it is unnecessary to do
so
and
the officer has given a person an invitation under paragraph
in
respect of the address,
the officer has given a person an invitation under section 9E of the
Representation of the People Act 1983 in respect of the address, or
a person is registered in respect of the address in a register
maintained by the officer and the person\xd5 s entitlement to remain
registered in the register has been confirmed.
In deciding whether it is necessary to supply a canvass form to an address
the registration officer must, in particular, consider whether supplying the
canvass form is likely to result in the officer finding out about people
residing at the address whom the officer might not otherwise find out about.
Registration officers to invite applications in year of second new canvass from those with
existing registrations
A registration officer in Great Britain must, on or as soon as reasonably
practicable after the relevant date, give a person an invitation to make a new
application for registration in a register maintained by the officer if the
person
has an entry in the register but has not had his or her entitlement to
remain registered confirmed, and
has not made a successful new application for registration in the
register.
\xd2 The relevant date\xd3 means whichever of the following comes first
the date on which, at the second new canvass, a canvass form is
completed and returned in respect of the address to which the
person\xd5 s entry in the register relates;
the date on which it appears to the officer that, at the second new
canvass, no canvass form will be completed and returned in respect
of that address;
31 October in the year of the second new canvass.
But the officer need not give an invitation at a time when
the officer has reason to believe, from records available to the officer,
that the person is no longer resident at that address, or
the person has made a new application for registration which has not
been determined.

Power to require additional information on poll cards at 2014 European Parliamentary election
Regulations under section 7(1) of the European Parliamentary Elections Act
2002 may include provision for the purpose of requiring a poll card to be
used at the 2014 European Parliamentary general election to include
information relating to changes made by Part 1 of this Act.
Certain provisions of this Part not to apply to persons within Part 5 or 6 below
In this Part of this Schedule, references to a person who has an entry in a
register do not include a person who is a relevant person for the purposes of
Part 5 or 6 of this Schedule.
Absent voting
Applicant for absent vote must have made successful new application for registration or had
registration confirmed
For the purposes of an absent voting application made on or after the
commencement date, a person is to be regarded as registered in a register in
Great Britain only if the person
was registered in the register immediately before the
commencement date and has had his or her entitlement to remain
registered confirmed, or
has made a successful new application for registration.
\xd2 Absent voting application\xd3 means an application under paragraph 3(1) or
(2) or 4(1) or (2) of Schedule 4 to the Representation of the People Act 2000.
This paragraph does not apply in relation to a person who is a relevant
person for the purposes of Part 5 or 6 of this Schedule.
Entitlement to absent vote ceases after first new canvass if no successful new application for
registration or confirmation of registration
Sub-paragraph (2) applies if, on the day on which a registration officer in
Great Britain publishes a register following the first new canvass
a person is shown in the absent voters\xd5 record as the result of an
application made in reliance on the person\xd5 s registration in the
register, and
the person was registered in the register immediately before the
commencement date and has not had his or her entitlement to
remain registered confirmed or made a successful new application
for registration in the register.
The officer must remove the person\xd5 s entry from the absent voters\xd5 record so
far as the entry concerns elections of the kind to which the register relates.
\xd2 Absent voters\xd5 record\xd3 means the record kept under paragraph 3 of
Schedule 4 to the Representation of the People Act 2000.
Sub-paragraph (5) applies if, on the day on which a registration officer in
Great Britain publishes a register following the first new canvass
a person is shown in an absent voters\xd5 list as the result of an
application made in reliance on the person\xd5 s registration in the
register, and
the person was registered in the register immediately before the
commencement date and has not had his or her entitlement to
remain registered confirmed or made a successful new application
for registration in the register.
The officer must remove the person\xd5 s entry from the absent voters\xd5 list.
\xd2 Absent voters\xd5 list\xd3 means the list mentioned in paragraph 5(2) or (3) of
Schedule
4 to the Representation of the People Act 2000.
If a registration officer removes a person\xd5 s entry from an absent voters\xd5
record or list, the officer must
notify the person in the prescribed manner, and
take any other prescribed steps.
This paragraph does not apply in relation to a person who is a relevant
person for the purposes of Part 5 or 6 of this Schedule.
Proxies to have made successful new application for registration or had registration confirmed
A person is to be regarded as registered in a register in Great Britain for the
purposes of paragraph 6(3) or (3A) of Schedule 4 to the Representation of the
People Act 2000 (as substituted by section
of this Act) only if the person
was registered in the register immediately before the
commencement date and has had his or her entitlement to remain
registered confirmed, or
has made a successful new application for registration.

or had registration confirmed until after first new canvass

ParaLine.String: Persons with existing registrations by virtue of declarations etc
Meaning of \xd2 relevant person\xd3
In this Part of this Schedule \xd2 relevant person\xd3 means a person who falls
within sub-paragraph (2) or (3).
A person falls within this sub-paragraph if the person
is for the time being registered in a register in pursuance of a
declaration of local connection, a service declaration or an overseas
elector\xd5 s declaration, and
has been registered
in pursuance of a declaration of that kind since
immediately before the commencement date.
A person falls within this sub-paragraph if the person
has for the time being an anonymous entry in a register, and
has had such an entry since immediately before the commencement
date.
Relevant person\xd5 s first renewal of registration after 3-month transitional period: successful
new application required
On the first occasion after the transitional period on which a relevant
person\xd5 s entry in a register comes up for renewal, the person is not entitled
to remain registered unless the person has made a successful new
application for registration (in addition to complying with any other
requirements).
\xd2 Transitional period\xd3 means the period of 3 months beginning with the
commencement date.
For the purposes of this paragraph, a relevant person\xd5 s entry in a register
comes up for renewal when an event mentioned in the applicable provision
occurs in relation to that entry.

section 7C(2) or 15(2) of the Representation of the People Act 1983 or
section 2(2) of the Representation of the People Act 1985, or
section 9C(1) of the Representation of the People Act 1983;
(as applicable).

ParaLine.String: Supplementary
Power to bring forward effect of paragraph 6
The Minister may by order provide for paragraph 6 to have effect as if the
reference to the third new canvass were a reference to the second new
canvass.
An order under sub-paragraph (1) may be made only in the period of
months beginning with 1 June in the year in which the second new canvass
begins.
A statutory instrument containing provision under sub-paragraph (1) only
is subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House of
Parliament (and section
(2) does not apply to it).
Power to make supplementary provision
The Minister may by order make provision for supplementing, or provision
incidental to, the provision made by this Schedule.
Interpretation of this Schedule
In this Schedule
\xd2 the first new canvass\xd3 means the first canvass under section 9D of the
Representation of the People Act 1983;
\xd2 prescribed\xd3 means prescribed by order made by the Minister;
\xd2 the second new canvass\xd3 means the second canvass under section 9D
of the Representation of the People Act 1983;
\xd2 the third new canvass\xd3 means the third canvass under section 9D of
the Representation of the People Act 1983.
In this Schedule references to publication of a register are to publication of
the revised version of the register under section 13(1)(a) of the
Representation of the People Act 1983.
In this Schedule
references to a person who is registered in a register immediately
before the commencement date include a person who becomes
registered in the register on or after that date as the result of an
application made before that date;
references to a person who has an anonymous entry in a register
immediately before the commencement date include a person whose
anonymous entry is made in the register on or after that date as the
result of an application made before that date.
For the purposes of this Schedule a document may be given to a person
by delivering it to the person,
by leaving it at the person\xd5 s address, or
by sending it to the person by post.
The Representation of the People Act 1983 and this Schedule are to have
effect as if this Schedule were contained in Part 1 of that Act.
References in an enactment other than one contained in this Schedule or the
Representation of the People Act 1983 to Part 1 of that Act include a
reference to this Schedule.

Splitting can occur anywhere within the Part/Chapter/CrossHeading structure of the clauses, or between Schedules. A split will never occur within a Schedule.
